            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Bengel's Gnomen",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jude 1:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Ὑμεῖς δὲ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀγαπητοὶ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "but ye, beloved",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") Thus also ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jude 1:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "μνήσθητε",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "remember",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") They therefore to whom Jude writes had also heard the other apostles.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀποστόλων",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "apostles",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") Jude does not exempt himself from the number of the apostles; for in the next verse he says, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to you",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", not, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to us",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 17, 18.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - A direct appeal is now introduced to the readers. Its object is to save them from being disconcerted by the rise of these impious men or beguiled by their pretensions. They are reminded, therefore, of apostolic words, by which from the beginning they had been taught to anticipate such perils and to be on their guard against them. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "But, beloved, remember ye the words which were",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (or, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "have been",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "spoken before of",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "cmt_word",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "spoken before of",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (i.e. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "by",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "the apostles of our Lord Jesus Christ.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "cmt_word",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "the apostles of our Lord Jesus Christ.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The Revised Version rightly restores the rendering \"but ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "ye",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", beloved,\" which the Authorized Version dropped. The older versions, Wickliffe, Tyndale, Cranmer, the Genevan, the Rhemish, agree in introducing this emphatic \"ye,\" which sets the readers in sharpest contrast to these \"murmurers,\" and gives greater point to Jude's appeal. The teaching of the apostles on the subject in hand is referred to as something by no means strange to them. The terms would naturally suggest that the readers had been themselves hearers of the apostles. They are not decisive, however, of the question whether oral or written communications, direct or indirect instructions, are in view. The indeterminate sense of the term \"apostle,\" and the general tenor of the reference, make it impossible to say that Jude ranks himself here among the twelve. The sentence would be more natural on the lips of one who was not himself an apostle. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "How that they told you there should be mockers in the last time, who should walk after their own ungodly lusts.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The Revised Version is more literally true to the original in giving this the direct form, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "how that they said, to you, In the last time there shall be mockers",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc. This does not necessarily imply, however, that written words are referred to, or that a quotation is being made. The tense of the verb, \"said,\" by which the words are introduced, points the other way. It means that they were ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "in the way of saying",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " such things, and makes it probable, therefore, that Jude refers to the substance of what the apostles were in the habit of saying about the future in their ordinary preaching and teaching. Christ's own prophecies on the subject of the end (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 24, 25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") would form the text for such declarations. We have examples of these apostolic predictions in the case of Paul (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 20:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Timothy 3:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), in that of John (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 John 2:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), in that of Peter (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Peter 3:2, 3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The last resembles the present passage most closely, the same unusual word for \"mockers,\" or \"scoffers,\" being common to both. The stress of the statement is again on the sensual impiety of these men, as appears from the strong and peculiar phrase with which the prediction closes, \"walking after their own lusts of ungodliness\" (Revised Version, margin). By \"the last time\" (with which compare the expressions in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Peter 1:5, 20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Peter 3:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 1:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.) is meant the time which closes the present order of things, and ushers in Christ's return. It was a Hebrew idea that time was divided into two great periods - \" this age\" and \"the age to come,\" which were parted by the coming of Messiah. The \"age to come,\"  or the Messianic age, was in principle introduced by Messiah's first advent, but it was to be finally brought in by his second advent - an event conceived to be near. The time which heralded the conclusive termination of the one period and entrance of the other was \"the last time\" - a time of evils and of portents marking the end of the old order. Jude 1:17",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]